Every recursive solution has:
1. <strong>Base case</strong> — when to stop
2. <strong>Recursive case</strong> — break problem into smaller subproblems
3. <strong>Memoization</strong> (optional) — cache repeated subproblems

<pre><code>// Classic: Fibonacci
// ❌ O(2^n) — exponential without memoization
public int fib(int n) {
    if (n <= 1) return n;
    return fib(n - 1) + fib(n - 2); // same subproblems recalculated!
}

// ✅ O(n) — with memoization
public int fib(int n, int[] memo) {
    if (n <= 1) return n;
    if (memo[n] != 0) return memo[n];  // already computed
    memo[n] = fib(n - 1, memo) + fib(n - 2, memo);
    return memo[n];
}</code></pre>

You won't write Fibonacci at REWE. But recursion appears in:

<pre><code>// 1. Tree traversal (category hierarchies)
@Entity
public class Category {
    @ManyToOne
    private Category parent;
    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "parent")
    private List&lt;Category&gt; children;
}

public List&lt;Category&gt; getAllDescendants(Category root) {
    List&lt;Category&gt; result = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    result.add(root);
    for (Category child : root.getChildren()) {
        result.addAll(getAllDescendants(child)); // recursive
    }
    return result;
}

// 2. Route optimization (backtracking)
public Route findOptimalRoute(List&lt;Stop&gt; remaining, Stop current, Route partial) {
    if (remaining.isEmpty()) return partial;
    Route best = null;
    for (Stop next : remaining) {
        Route candidate = findOptimalRoute(
            without(remaining, next), next, partial.add(next));
        if (best == null || candidate.cost() < best.cost())
            best = candidate;
    }
    return best;
}

// 3. JSON/Config parsing (nested structures)
public Map&lt;String, Object&gt; flatten(Map&lt;String, Object&gt; nested, String prefix) {
    Map&lt;String, Object&gt; flat = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();
    for (var entry : nested.entrySet()) {
        String key = prefix.isEmpty() ? entry.getKey() : prefix + "." + entry.getKey();
        if (entry.getValue() instanceof Map m) {
            flat.putAll(flatten(m, key)); // recurse into nested maps
        } else {
            flat.put(key, entry.getValue());
        }
    }
    return flat;
}</code></pre>

Memoization IS caching applied to function results:

<pre><code>// Academic: memo array
int[] memo = new int[n + 1];

// Production: Spring Cache (same principle!)
@Cacheable("route-costs")
public BigDecimal calculateRouteCost(String routeId) {
    // expensive computation — only runs once per routeId
    return routeService.computeCost(routeId);
}

// Production: ConcurrentHashMap as local cache
private final Map&lt;String, DriverStats&gt; statsCache = new ConcurrentHashMap&lt;&gt;();

public DriverStats getStats(String driverId) {
    return statsCache.computeIfAbsent(driverId,
        id -> heavyStatsCalculation(id)); // computed once
}</code></pre>

<strong>Connection to interview:</strong> When asked about recursion, show you understand the bridge to production caching: same problem (repeated computation), same solution (store and reuse).

A queue is FIFO. That same concept scales from in-memory to distributed:

<pre><code>// Level 1: In-memory queue (single JVM)
Queue&lt;Task&gt; tasks = new ArrayDeque&lt;&gt;();
tasks.offer(new Task("process-delivery"));
Task next = tasks.poll(); // FIFO

// Level 2: BlockingQueue (producer-consumer in same JVM)
BlockingQueue&lt;DeliveryEvent&gt; queue = new LinkedBlockingQueue&lt;&gt;(1000);
// Producer thread:
queue.put(event); // blocks if full
// Consumer thread:
DeliveryEvent e = queue.take(); // blocks if empty

// Level 3: Kafka (distributed queue across services)
// Same FIFO concept, but:
// - Persistent (survives restarts)
// - Partitioned (parallel consumers)
// - Replayable (consumer can re-read)
@KafkaListener(topics = "delivery-events")
public void handle(DeliveryEvent event) {
    // same consumer logic, different scale
}</code></pre>

Kafka decides which partition gets a message using hashing:

<pre><code>// Kafka's default partitioner:
partition = hash(key) % numPartitions

// Same driver's events always go to same partition → ordered!
kafkaTemplate.send("driver-events", driverId, event);
// driverId = key → hash(driverId) % 6 = always partition 3
// All events for this driver arrive in order

// Why this matters:
// - Ordering guarantee is PER PARTITION
// - If you need events for entity X in order → use X's ID as key
// - If you don't need order → use round-robin (null key)</code></pre>

<strong>Consistent hashing in caching (Redis Cluster):</strong>
When you add/remove a Redis node, consistent hashing ensures only ~1/n keys need to move, not all keys. Same principle as Kafka partition rebalancing.
